<doc id="214920" wikidata="Q1122368" url="?curid=214920" title="Estrie">
<text>Estrie () is an administrative region of Quebec that comprises the Eastern Townships. &quot;Estrie&quot;, a French neologism, was coined as a derivative of &quot;est&quot;, &quot;east&quot;. Originally settled by anglophones, today it is about 90 per cent francophone. Anglophones are concentrated in Lennoxville, home of the region&#x27;s only English-speaking university, Bishop&#x27;s University. The Eastern Townships School Board runs 20 elementary schools, three high schools, and a learning centre.

The region originally consisted of 6 regional county municipalities. In 2021, La Haute-Yamaska &amp; Brome-Missisquoi joined Estrie, transferring from Montérégie.

==Economy==

While the economy of the area is mainly based on agriculture, forestry, and mining, tourist attractions include four Sépaq parks: Yamaska, Mont-Orford, Frontenac, and Mont-Mégantic, ski resorts at Mont Brome and Mont Orford, and agritourism.

